<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>美国之音学习英语</title><description>VOA学习英语全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> http://voanews.com <item><title><![CDATA[Taylor Swift Headed to This Law school, in Theory]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/taylor-swift-headed-to-this-law-school-in-theory/7338992.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023 年 11 月 3 日星期五 21:55:15 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/42899fd9- 321a-4bee-b0b4-ca9ec5894e62_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;文件 - 泰勒·斯威夫特 (Taylor Swift) 出席洛杉矶《泰勒·斯威夫特：时代巡演》首映式，美国加利福尼亚州，2023 年 10 月 11 日。（路透社/Mario Anzuoni/档案照片）&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;南达科他大学法学教授肖恩·卡默 (Sean Kammer) 的朋友告诉他，他们不确定他即将上课的严肃性泰勒·斯威夫特 (Taylor Swift) 的粉丝卡默 (Kammer) 表示：“我知道这听起来&lt;strong>;荒谬&lt;/strong>;，至少乍一看&lt;/strong>;是这样。”斯威夫特本人。 “但事实并非如此。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kammer 的课程名为“泰勒·斯威夫特效应”，计划于春季举行。据信，这是法学院开设的第一门以这位美国著名歌手为主题的课程。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;6 月份参加明尼苏达州明尼阿波利斯市的斯威夫特音乐会后，卡默表示，他&lt;strong>;受到启发&lt;/strong>;发展写作课。它适用于二年级和三年级的法学院学生。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;该课程将研究艺术家与法律的关系，包括她重新录制六张专辑和相关的&lt;strong>;版权&lt;/strong>;问题，Kammer说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;它还将研究个人的经历和信仰如何影响他们对法律的理解——就像对她的歌曲有不同的理解一样。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;关于流行文化的法律课程是并不少见。他们还引起了人们对提供这些课程的学校的关注。多年来，电视节目《火线》启发了许多刑法课程。 2022 年，弗吉尼亚大学法学院开设了基于《继承》节目的公司法课程。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;然而，以单个公众人物为中心的法律课程很少见。但佐治亚州立大学法学院目前正在开设一门以音乐家里克·罗斯的法律生活为基础的课程。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;波士顿大学法学教授杰西卡·西尔贝帮助撰写了一本关于流行文化和法律的书。她说，学生通常对体育、新技术和名人等科目更感兴趣。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Silbey 在版权课上教授斯威夫特的专辑重新录制，以教授音乐行业的合同法。她说这位歌手的成功故事和她所经历的事情为法律提供了很好的教训。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;南达科他州法学院并不是第一所提供斯威夫特课程的学校。加州大学伯克利分校最近宣布即将推出基于斯威夫特商业经验的商业课程。斯坦福大学、纽约大学和德克萨斯大学也提供了受 Swift 启发的课程。但 Kammer 的课程是她对音乐和职业生涯的第一次法律探索。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kammer 还教授法律史。他说他计划检查一些 Swift 歌曲，以了解如何理解这些歌曲的歌词和某些法律文本。他说他的班级还将研究理解法律的方法的优缺点。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;我是吉尔·罗宾斯。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;凯伦斯隆为路透社报道了这个故事。格雷戈里·斯塔切尔为美国之音英语学习频道改编了这个故事。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;__________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>; &lt;/h2>; &lt;h2>;这个故事中的文字&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;荒谬&lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;形容词&lt;/em>;。极其愚蠢或不合理&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;一眼&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。快速、不感兴趣的眼神&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;激发灵感&lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;v&lt;/em>;。让（某人）想做某事：让（某人）知道要做什么或创造什么&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;版权&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。在一段时间内成为唯一复制、出版和销售书籍或音乐唱片的合法权利&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;文本&lt;/strong>;–n。一篇文章&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 04 Nov 2023 06:07:09 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Michelangelo“s “Secret Room“ to Open for Visitors]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/michelangelo-s-secret-room-to-open-for-visitors/7337444.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023 年 11 月 3 日星期五 21:58:00 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/0ca2b689- bfd7-4e39-9411-0a85fb77b986_cx0_cy10_cw0_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;在房间的墙壁上可以看到一些专家认为出自米开朗基罗之手的精美木炭画2023 年 10 月 31 日星期二，意大利中部佛罗伦萨美第奇教堂内用于储存煤炭，直至 1955 年。（Francesco Fanfani，美联社、HO）&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>; &lt;p>;游客很快就能参观意大利佛罗伦萨市美第奇教堂内一个长期隐藏的空间。这个小空间的墙壁上画有一些专家认为可能是著名艺术家米开朗基罗创作的图画。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;密室很小 - 10 米 x 3 米。 1975 年，官员们在寻找美第奇教堂的新出口时发现了这个房间。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;时任博物馆馆长保罗·达尔·波杰托 (Paolo Dal Poggetto) 坚信这些画是米开朗基罗的作品。现任董事保拉·达戈斯蒂诺 (Paola D&#39;Agostino) 说道。关于这个问题的争论从那时开始，一直持续到今天。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;达戈斯蒂诺表示，米开朗基罗的绘画专家在发现这些作品时并不相信他创作了这些作品 50几年前。她补充道，“其他人的观点更为温和，他们认为有些可能是米开朗基罗的作品，有些可能是追随者的作品。因此争论仍在继续。”&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;这个房间一直被用来储存煤炭，直到 1955 年。然后它被关闭并被遗忘了多年，位于一种称为活板门的特殊开口之下。活板门隐藏在&lt;strong>;家具&lt;/strong>;下面。这些图画本身是在两层石膏下发现的，石膏是一种用于使墙壁和天花板变得光滑的物质。&lt;/p>; &lt;div >;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com /b8481eb6-0f25-44a5-97eb-8af5e279f8bf_w900.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;活板门通向一间房间，墙壁上有精致的木炭画，一些专家认为这些画是米开朗基罗的作品，位于意大利中部佛罗伦萨的美第奇教堂内，星期二，2023 年 10 月 31 日。（美联社照片/Luigi Navarra）&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/>;&lt;span>;里面可以看到通往一间房间的活板门，房间的墙上挂着精致的木炭画，一些专家认为这些画是米开朗基罗的作品意大利中部佛罗伦萨美第奇教堂，2023 年 10 月 31 日星期二。（美联社照片/Luigi Navarra）&lt;/span>;&lt;/div>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Dal Poggetto 相信米开朗基罗隐藏了在太空中躲避教皇克莱门特七世的愤怒。这位艺术家支持了一个推翻美第奇家族的短命共和国。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;在房间里，这位艺术家为他的一些项目画画。其中包括据信是朱利亚诺·德·美第奇腿的图画。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;从 11 月 15 日开始，四人小组将能够参观该房间约 15 分钟。参观者在主博物馆门票 10 美元的基础上，还需额外支付 20 美元。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;博物馆表示，由于需要减少参观人数，因此限制参观人数艺术品在光线下&lt;strong>;曝光&lt;/strong>;。每周最多可有 100 名访客进入该房间。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;我是 John Russell。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;约翰·拉塞尔改编自美联社和路透社的报道。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;_________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;这个故事中的文字&lt;/h2>; &lt;/ div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;家具&lt;/strong>; &lt;em>;– n.&lt;/em>;椅子、桌子、床等&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong >;暴露&lt;/strong>; &lt;em>;- n.&lt;/em>;受某事影响或经历某事的事实或状况&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt; div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>; &lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 04 Nov 2023 06:07:09 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[“The Boy on Graves-End Road,“ by Caty Weaver]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/the-boy-on-graves-end-road-caty-weaver/3568894.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023 年 11 月 3 日星期五 21:59:00 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;video poster=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/7c8a764e- 35a4-4d48-902d-152db478d470_tv_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; src=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;width:100%&quot; 控件>;&lt;/video>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;&lt;/small>;&lt;/div >;&lt;video poster=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/7c8a764e-35a4-4d48-902d-152db478d470_tv_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; src=&quot;T&quot; style=&quot;width:100%&quot; 控件>;&lt;/video>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;T&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>;&lt;video poster=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews. com/7c8a764e-35a4-4d48-902d-152db478d470_tv_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; src=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;width:100%&quot; 控件>;&lt;/video>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;&lt;/small >;&lt;/div>;&lt;video poster=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/7c8a764e-35a4-4d48-902d-152db478d470_tv_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; src=&quot;7&quot; style=&quot;width: 100%”控制>;&lt;/video>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;7&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>;&lt;audio src=&quot;https://av.voanews.com/clips/ VLE/2015/10/12/f8c70019-f17e-40c1-a19c-f1b27518475b_original.mp3&quot;controls>;&lt;/audio>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;Caty Weaver 的《格雷夫斯尽头路上的男孩》 &lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; &lt;em>;编者注：这是一个针对英语学习者的每周多媒体美国短篇故事系列。每个故事都有视频、音频、测验和教师教学计划。希望您喜欢阅读和聆听这个故事！请在下面留下您的问题和意见。&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; &lt;em>;10 月 31 日是万圣节。本着这个古老节日的精神，我们呈现一个由我们自己的记者兼制片人凯蒂·韦弗撰写的故事。它的名字叫“格雷夫斯恩德路上的男孩”。&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />;凯莉·瑞安正在做晚饭。她 10 岁的儿子本杰明正在客厅看电视。或者至少她认为他是。&lt;br />;凯利：“本尼男孩，你想要黑豆还是红豆？”&lt;br />;本：“红豆，妈妈。”&lt;br />;凯利：“啊！别那样做，本。你&lt;strong>;吓&lt;/strong>;我半死！你现在就明白了……”&lt;br />;本悄悄地走到她身后。&lt;br />; &lt;br />; 凯利：“我会回复你的，臭东西！”&lt;br />; 凯利走向电话，但她一把手放在电话上，铃声就停止了。&lt;br />; 凯利：“太奇怪了。哦，豆子！”&lt;br />;凯莉将注意力转回到烹饪上。她刚一开口，电话就又响了。&lt;br />; 凯莉：“亲爱的，你能接听吗？”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 本：“喂？哦，嗨。是的，我记得.当然，听起来很有趣。让我问问我妈妈。你能坚持吗？她可能想和你妈妈谈谈。哦，嗯，好的。明天见。”&lt;br />; 凯利：“本，你的米饭和豆子是放在桌子上。我们吃饭吧。”&lt;br />; &lt;br />; 凯莉：“那么，那通电话是关于什么的？”&lt;br />; 本：“那是华莱士·格雷。你在课堂上认识他。他想明天玩。放学后我可以和他一起回家吗？拜托，妈妈？我下班后在这里等你很无聊。”&lt;br />; 凯莉：“但是，我什至不认识他的父母。也许我应该谈谈”&lt;br />; BEN：“你不能，妈妈。他和他的保姆在一起。他说他的父母要到今晚晚些时候才会回家，他们会在他早上去学校之前离开。拜托妈妈，华莱士就住在格雷夫斯安德路。从这里步行五分钟。请，好吗？”&lt;br />; 凯莉：“好吧，好吧。这家伙到底有什么了不起的？你有很多朋友可以一起玩。”&lt;br />; BEN：“我知道。但华莱士不同。他有很多想象力。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 学校周过去了，本几乎每天都和华莱士一起回家。凯莉注意到儿子的变化。他看起来很疲惫而且性格孤僻。他的眼睛似乎并没有真正看着她。他们看起来……毫无生气。周五晚上，她决定他们需要谈谈。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 凯莉：“亲爱的，你怎么了？你看起来很累，很疏远。有什么问题吗？你和你的孩子有没有新朋友吵架了？”&lt;br />; BEN：“不，妈妈。我们玩得很开心。我们没有任何问题。你为什么不喜欢华莱士？你甚至不认识他，但是你不信任他。”&lt;br />; 凯利：“本杰明，你在说什么？我并不讨厌华莱士。你是对的，我不认识他。你只是看起来不像你自己.过去几个晚上你一直很安静。”&lt;br />;BEN：“对不起，妈妈。我想我只是累了。我和华莱士玩得很开心。我们玩警察和强盗等游戏，但它们看起来如此真实，以至于有一半的时间我感觉自己身处另一个世界。这很难解释。就像，就像......”&lt;br />; KELLY：“我认为你正在寻找的词因为是&lt;strong>;激烈&lt;/strong>;。”&lt;br />; BEN：“是的，就是这样 - 很激烈。”&lt;br />; KELLY：“好吧，告诉我今天的情况。你玩了什么类型的游戏？”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; BEN：“我们是火车劫匪。或者说华莱士就是。我是一名站长。华莱士正在一列长长的火车上奔跑，从一节车厢跑到另一节车厢。他从乘客那里偷走了很多钱和黄金。我紧追在他身后，以最快的速度追赶他。最后他从火车上跳进车站逃走了。但我挡住了他的路。他在站台上抓住了一名女子。她尖叫着“不，不！”但他大喊“让我过去，否则她就死了”。所以我让他走了。”&lt;br />; 凯莉：“然后发生了什么？”&lt;br />; 本：“嗯，这就是&lt;strong>;奇怪&lt;/strong>;，而且就像你说的，很激烈。华莱士把那位女士扔到了铁轨上。并笑了。他说这就是游戏中邪恶角色所做的事情。他们总是做最坏的打算。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 后来，本上床睡觉后，凯莉打开十一点新闻。她只半在听，准备了一份要处理的事情清单。第二天，万圣节。&lt;br />; 凯莉：“好吧，让我们看看，杂货店购物，万圣节装饰，狗要去美容师那里，我要去五金店，清理花园......&lt; br />; [背景电视]&lt;br />; 新闻播音员：“有报道称，她似乎被从站台上推到了迎面而来的火车的路径上。事情发生在今天的高峰时段。一些目击者称看到两个男孩在该女子附近奔跑玩耍。但警方表示，他们没有在车站的监控摄像头上看到任何类似的图像。&lt;br />;凯利：“不！不可能。车站距离车站有一个小时的路程。他们不可能到达那里。怎么可能他们？只是巧合而已。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 那天晚上，风低沉而孤独。凯利睡得很少。她梦见自己在火车站等本。然后，她看到他在另一边，正带着另一个小男孩跑着。&lt;br />;她想，这一定是华莱士。小男孩进进出出，又消失在人们的视线里。然后，突然，他停下来，目光越过铁轨——直视着她。&lt;br />;他没有脸。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />;周六的早晨，阳光灿烂，是一个凉爽的十月。天。凯利给本做了鸡蛋和吐司，看着他高兴地吃着。&lt;br />; 凯利：“你知道吗，本尼小子，昨天在火车站确实有一个女人受伤了。她实际上被火车撞了。这不是很奇怪吗？” ？”&lt;br />;她看着本。&lt;br />;本：“你什么意思，妈妈？”&lt;br />;凯利：“嗯，你和华莱士昨天正在玩那个游戏。关于在火车站的事情……你说他把一个女人从站台上扔下来，然后她就被火车撞死了。”&lt;br />; 凯利连说出这句话都觉得自己像个傻瓜。她正在和一个十岁的孩子说话，这个孩子一直在和另一个十岁的孩子玩一个想象中的游戏。她在想什么？&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; BEN：“我说过我们昨天玩过这个？我玩过？嗯。不，我们几天前玩过这个，我想。这真的很棒。”游戏，真的很激烈。昨天我们玩海盗。我要扮演海盗船阿格号上的弗兰克船长。&lt;br />;“华莱士是戴维，大副。但他试图反抗并接管这艘船，所以我让他走上木板。戴维走进海里淹死了。华莱士告诉我，我必须命令他走木板。他说这就是邪恶海盗所做的事。”&lt;br />; 凯利：“我想他是对的。我不认识任何海盗，但我确实听说他们非常邪恶！”&lt;br />; BEN：“今天你出去办事的时候我可以和华莱士一起玩吗？请问，妈妈？我不想去购物和布置万圣节装饰品。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 凯莉：“哦，无所谓了。大概吧。我会在五点三十分左右到华莱士家接你，这样你就可以准备好玩“不给糖就捣蛋”游戏。他又住在哪里？&lt;br />; BEN：“格雷夫斯恩德路。我不知道门牌号，但两边只有两栋房子。他的就是左边第二栋。”&lt;br />;凯莉：“好吧。我觉得这很容易。你还想让我为你挑选一套&lt;strong>;幽灵&lt;/strong>;服装吗？”&lt;br />; 本：“是的。哦，你猜怎么着，妈妈：华莱士说他也是鬼！我想我们会一起在附近出没。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 那天凯利去的地方都很拥挤。她光是在市场就花了一个半小时。当她回到家时，为万圣节装饰房子很困难。&lt;br />;但最终她如愿以偿。&lt;br />;凯莉：“哦，天哪，已经五个了。我什至没有本的服装”&lt;br />;她跳上车，开往威尔逊大道。派对商店就在几个街区之外。&lt;br />;凯利很快就找到了本想要的幽灵服装。她买了它并走出了商店。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 艾琳：“嘿，凯莉！好久不见。本杰明怎么样？”&lt;br />; 凯莉：“艾琳！哇，这是很高兴见到你。马特怎么样？自从学年开始以来我们一直很忙，我们还没见过任何人！”&lt;br />; 艾琳：“马特很好。嗯，他上个月摔断了手臂，所以没有运动。他。这让他发疯，但至少他现在有很多时间上学！”&lt;br />; 凯莉：那很好，是的。&lt;br />; 艾琳：“无论如何，马特想知道为什么本尼男孩从来没有不再来了。上周放学后我们看到他在附近跑来跑去。看起来他玩得很开心，但他总是一个人。我们不需要安排一个玩耍日期。本应该知道这一点。你只要告诉他不再过来了。上周放学后我们带他在附近跑来跑去。看起来他玩得很开心，但他总是一个人。我们不需要安排一个玩耍日期。本应该知道这一点。你只要告诉他过来。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 凯莉：“等等，等一下。独自的？独自一人是什么意思？放学后，他开始和一个新朋友华莱士一起玩，就像过去一周的每一天一样。本并不孤单。华莱士·格雷，就是这样。你认识他吗？马特是吗？”&lt;br />; 艾琳：“哦，凯尔。凯利，我确信他是个好孩子。我不认识他，但别担心，本对朋友很有品味，我们知道这一点！我确信他并不孤单，他可能只是在玩捉迷藏什么的。我不是故意让你担心的。我想每个人都因为今天早上发生在戈德温男孩身上的事情而感到紧张。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />;凯莉突然感到寒冷和害怕。什么戈德温男孩？他发生了什么事？她不确定她自己想知道，但她不得不问。&lt;br />; 艾琳：“弗兰克·戈德温最小的儿子，戴维，五岁。你认识弗兰克，我们称他为队长。他曾经是一名船长。嗯，今天早上救援队在布莱克哈特湖找到了戴维。他们还找到了他爸爸为他制作的一艘小玩具船。戴维和他的父亲将其命名为 Argh。戴维一定是想驾驭它。太悲伤了。”&lt;br />; 凯利：“等等，他死了？&lt;br />; 艾琳：“是的。戴维淹死了。”&lt;br />; 凯利：“布莱克哈特湖在哪里？”&lt;br />; 艾琳：“是的。”就在格雷夫斯恩德路 (Graves-End Road) 旁边，就在那个小&lt;strong>;墓地&lt;/strong>;后面。这就是为什么他们称之为格雷夫斯恩德 (Graves-End)。凯利，你要去哪里？”&lt;br />; 凯利：“我得去本杰明。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />;凯利沿着主街奔跑。她不知道华莱士·格雷是谁，也不知道他是如何参与这一切的。但她不信任他，她知道她的孩子正处于危险之中。&lt;br />;最后她到了格雷夫斯恩德路。&lt;br />;BEN：“两边只有两栋房子。”&lt;br />;她记得什么本告诉过她的。&lt;br />;艾琳：“就在那个小墓地后面。”&lt;br />;还有艾琳告诉她的。凯莉下了车，沿着街道走去。她环顾四周。&lt;br />;BEN：“这是左边第二个。”&lt;br />;她可以看到湖。在这个万圣节之夜，天空变暗，起了一些雾气。但没有第二套房子。眼前的却是青草和白色的大石头。墓地。凯利穿过大门，走进坟场。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 凯利：“本？”&lt;br />; 没有回应。她继续走。&lt;br />;凯利：“本？回答我。我知道你在这里。”&lt;br />;还是没有回答。但风吹过，一些树叶开始在墓碑周围跳舞。凯莉慢慢地走向坟墓。突然，天色黑了下来，黑得她什么也看不见。她感觉到有一股力量在推着她。它试图将她推离坟墓。但她知道她必须留下来。&lt;br />; 凯利：“本杰明·欧文·奥尔，这是你的母亲。马上出来！”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 没有人回答，除了声音吹着的风。黑暗消散了。银色的月光直射在她面前的古老墓碑上。但凯利已经知道她会看到谁的名字。&lt;br />; 凯利：“华莱士·格雷。1900 年 10 月 31 日至 1910 年 10 月 31 日。有些人安息后是最好的。”&lt;/p>; &lt;div >;&lt; img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/7F2F5D83-DA26-4984-9656-4075CAD712C4_w268_h151.png&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/>;&lt;span>;&lt;/ span>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; &lt;br />;凯利深吸了一口气。然后...&lt;br />; 凯利：“华莱士·格雷，这次玩耍约会结束了！把我的儿子还给我。华莱士，你已经暂停了。”&lt;br />; 突然，地面像一座小火山一样向上冲去。泥土、树枝和&lt;strong>;蠕虫&lt;/strong>;飞过凯利的头顶，再次落下——她的儿子紧随其后，落在她旁边。&lt;br />; 本：（咳嗽，&lt;strong>;窒息&lt;/strong>;） &lt;br />; 凯利：“本！本！”&lt;br />; 本：（咳嗽、窒息）“妈妈，妈妈！你在吗？我看不见。我眼睛里全是污垢。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; 凯利：“本，我在这里，我在这里，宝贝，就在这里。哦，亲爱的本尼男孩。你能呼吸吗？你真的好吗？发生了什么事？你在里面多久了？在那里？”&lt;br />; 本：“我不知道，妈妈。但我不喜欢它。我不喜欢华莱士住的地方。我想回家。”&lt;br />; 凯莉：“哦，我也是，亲爱的。来吧，本，用你的手臂搂住我。来吧。&lt;br />; 本：“妈妈，还有一件事......”&lt;br />; 凯莉：“那是什么，本？”&lt;br />; BEN：“我不想在万圣节当鬼。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;_________________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;对于教师&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;本课基于 CALLA 方法，教授“Act It Out”策略，以帮助学生理解故事。&lt;/p>; &lt;p >; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;脚本&lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;________________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;这个故事中的文字&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;&lt;强>;惊吓&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;v&lt;/em>;。使（某人）变得害怕&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;墓地&lt;/strong>;- &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。埋葬死人的地方：墓地&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;激烈&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;adj&lt;/em>;。一个人的：非常严肃&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;平台&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。铁轨旁边的平坦区域，人们在那里等待火车或地铁&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;墓碑&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;n.&lt;/em>;一块石头，标志着死者所在的地方被埋葬，通常上面有这个人的名字和出生日期和死亡日期&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;奇怪&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;adj&lt;/em>;。不寻常或奇怪&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;幽灵&lt;/strong>;- &lt;em>;n。 &lt;/em>;死者的灵魂被认为生活在看不见的世界中或在活着的人面前出现&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;蠕虫&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。一种又长又瘦的动物，身体柔软，没有腿或骨头，经常生活在地下&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;窒息&lt;/strong>; -&lt;em>; v&lt;/em>;。变得无法呼吸，通常是因为喉咙里有东西卡住或者空气不利于呼吸&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;br />; &lt;em>;现在轮到你在这个故事中使用这些词了。在评论部分，使用这些单词之一写一个句子，我们将提供有关您使用词汇和语法的反馈。或者将其发布到&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.facebook.com/voaspecialenglish&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;我们的 Facebook 页面&lt;/a>;。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; >;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/一个>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 04 Nov 2023 06:07:09 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[“In Which“ and “To Which“]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/in-which-and-to-which-/7337731.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023 年 11 月 3 日星期五 22:05:27 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/01000000- c0a8-0242-ea46-08dbdb1b669a_r1_s.png&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>; &lt;div>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;您好！本周&lt;em>;请教老师&lt;/em>;，我们回答了一个有关使用介词“which”的问题。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;问题&lt;/strong>; &lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;亲爱的美国之音请教老师，&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;我是来自日本的 Shohei。我每天都喜欢美国之音学习英语的很多内容。我有一个关于使用“which”的语法问题，例如，在其中，其中，来自哪个，等等。以英语为母语的人如何立即决定使用正确的介词？我无法理解这些差异。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;致以诚挚的问候，&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;谢谢您 (^^)！&lt;/p>; &lt;/ div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;回答&lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;感谢您的来信，翔平。这是一个好问题。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;当我们将“which”与介词一起使用时，在书面英语中大多是用来表示地点、时间或方式（或某事物的方式）正在发生。）&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;最常用的介词“which”是“in”和“to”。 &lt;a href=&quot;https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/use-a-language-corpus-to-improve-your-vocabulary/7189316.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;当代美国英语语料库&lt; /a>; 显示“in”的使用频率是“to”的五倍。它们都占所有带有“which”的介词用法的 60% 以上。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;很多时候，“inwhich”和“towhich”被用作部分英语中的一个表达方式。它们包括“程度”、“方式”和“方式”。以下是一些示例：&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;我们可以探索&lt;u>;自然变化的方式&lt;/u>;。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;我们的未来取决于人类阻止气候变化的&lt;u>;程度&lt;/u>; 。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;粉丝对教练谈论的&lt;u>;方式&lt;/u>;不满意团队。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;还有一件事，如果您不确定哪个介词与“which”一起使用，那么“in”是一个不错的选择，因为它最常用.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Shohei，请告诉我们这个解释是否对您有帮助。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;您对美式英语有疑问吗？请发送电子邮件至 &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:learningenglish@voanews.com&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;learningenglish@voanews.com&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;那就是&lt;em>;请教老师&lt;/em>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;我是 Gena Bennett。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt; p>;&lt;em>;吉娜·贝内特 (Gena Bennett) 为美国之音英语学习频道撰写了本课程。&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 04 Nov 2023 06:07:09 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Fans of K-pop Star Can Talk with His AI Twin]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/fans-of-k-pop-star-can-talk-with-his-ai-twin/7337475.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023 年 11 月 2 日星期四 21:55:59 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/5ed263c8- 10a4-4b99-be0a-65596635507e_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;文件 - 韩国流行音乐音乐家 Mark Tuan 于2022 年 11 月 20 日。（摄影：Jordan Strauss/Invision/AP，档案）&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;听众希望与他们支持的音乐家有亲近感。大多数人都会抓住与他们最喜欢的艺术家一对一交谈的机会。但名人很少有时间参加这种会议。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;那么，下一个最好的事情是什么？&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;对于 Mark Tuan，他的新唱片 &lt;em>;Fallin&lt;/em>;周五发布，正在创建一个&lt;strong>;数字化身&lt;/strong>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这位来自加利福尼亚州洛杉矶的台裔美国艺人是韩国组合 Got7 的前成员。他与 Soul Machines 合作创建了一个名为“数字标记”的“数字&lt;strong>;双胞胎&lt;/strong>;”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;通过这样做，Tuan 成为第一个将自己的肖像与人工智能联系起来的名人(AI) 程序 OpenAI 的 GPT。该技术允许粉丝与 Tuan 的化身进行一对一的交谈。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“这是非常不同的。这不是真正的我，但它就是我，”他谈到 Digital Mark 时说道。 “粉丝们也可以与他&lt;strong>;互动&lt;/strong>;，这是一件&lt;strong>;很酷&lt;/strong>;的事情。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Greg Cross 是 Soul Machines 的负责人。他将数字标记视为粉丝互动的未来。 Cross 表示，这项技术将如何改变粉丝与名人和公司的互动方式，我们才刚刚开始。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Tuan 对 Digital Mark 的希望是，随着技术的进步，粉丝与他的关系也会随之进步。人工智能双胞胎。他还希望他们能用英语以外的语言与他交流。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;让 Digital Mark 看起来像真正的 Mark Tuan，需要做很多工作。 Tuan 不得不花费几天的时间穿着&lt;strong>;紧身衣&lt;/strong>;拍摄来捕捉他的动作。他做出不同的表情，这样数字标记就能捕捉到他的情绪。他还花了很多时间录制自己的声音。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;现在，Digital Mark 就站在一处。但 Tuan 表示，也许有一天他们也会拥有数字标记。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这项技术还处于早期阶段。 Tuan 说 Digital Mark 一直在谈论一个不存在的音乐事件。但他希望看到化身将如何进展。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;粉丝们已经使用 Digital Mark 与 Tuan 就活动日期和新音乐进行互动。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;至于担心这将如何进行对于未来可以使用的技术，Tuan 充满希望，但也有一些担忧。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我看过很多机器人占领世界的电影，”他开玩笑说。 “你永远不知道会发生什么，但我认为这真的很酷。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;我是格雷戈里·斯塔切尔。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;玛丽亚谢尔曼为美联社报道了这个故事。格雷戈里·斯塔切尔为美国之音英语学习频道改编了这个故事。 &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;这个故事中的文字&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;数字&lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;形容词&lt;/em>;。使用计算机技术或以计算机技术为特征&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;化身&lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。在计算机屏幕上，尤其是在计算机游戏或社交媒体上代表特定计算机用户的人或动物的图片&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;双胞胎&lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;n&lt; /em>;.同一个母亲同时出生的两个婴儿中的一个&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;酷&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;形容词&lt;/em>;。非常时尚、时尚或有吸引力，特别是年轻人普遍认可的方式&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;互动&lt;/strong>; - &lt;em>;v&lt;/em>;。与其他人交谈或做事&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;紧身衣&lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;。一件紧密合身并覆盖身体（除了腿，有时还包括手臂）的衣服&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href =&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 03 Nov 2023 06:07:03 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Environmental Group Says Few Companies Meet Water Use Targets]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/environmental-group-says-few-companies-meet-water-use-targets/7337607.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;Thu, 02 Nov 2023 21:56:00 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/01000000-c0a8-0242-8827-08dbdbc37b25_cx0_cy8_cw0_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;Coca-Cola cans move down a conveyer belt in the Swire Coca-Cola bottling plant Oct. 20, 2023, in Denver. (AP Photo/Brittany Peterson)&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;Major corporations in industries that produce clothing, food, drinks and technology services use a lot of water.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;However, many companies say they want to be more responsible about the freshwater they use. &lt;strong>;Drought&lt;/strong>;, floods and extreme weather also threaten their supply chains.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The nonprofit environmental group Ceres ranked 72 companies for their &lt;strong>;sustainability&lt;/strong>; efforts. Ceres said few of the businesses are close to reaching the 2030 goals set by the group, which is based in Boston, Massachusetts.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Last year, Ceres launched an effort to push companies with large water usage to protect water resources. Recently, the group released a study that included the corporations Coca-Cola, General Mills and Amazon.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“There&#39;s no doubt that companies need to do better,” said Kirsten James. She is a program director for water at Ceres.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Ceres said the companies were chosen from four industries based on their size and use of water. They were ranked based on several &lt;strong>;factors&lt;/strong>;, including promises to protect the amount and quality of the water they use, as well as the environments that supply it. They were also tested on whether they helped improve &lt;strong>;access&lt;/strong>; to water and &lt;strong>;sanitation&lt;/strong>; in communities where they do business. Ceres used publicly available information, including information the companies provided to the government through March.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;None of the companies scored above 70 percent of the points available. Some were considered to be on track to meet the goals set by the nonprofit group, with scores of at least 50 percent.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Coca-Cola said its water use in 2022 was 10 percent more &lt;strong>;efficient&lt;/strong>; compared to 2015. The company said it hopes to have 100 percent circular water use. That is where all water is used and returned to the &lt;strong>;watersheds&lt;/strong>; it has been drawn from.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But the company did not say how likely it was to reach that target, nor how much progress it has made. Coca-Cola also said producing its products does not use as much water as growing what goes into the products it sells.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“The agricultural ingredients that we use use &lt;strong>;vastly&lt;/strong>; more water to produce than the actual manufacturing process,” said Michael Goltzman. He is vice president of Coca Cola and a sustainability head.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Reports say technology companies, like Amazon and Apple, use a lot of water to cool the computers in their large data centers. The Ceres study rated both companies below 20 percent progress toward the nonprofit&#39;s targets.&lt;/p>; &lt;div >;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/01000000-0aff-0242-9c30-08dbc9b900a1_w900.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;FILE - The familiar sign at the Amazon Robotic Sorting Fulfillment Center in Madison County, Miss., Thursday, Aug. 11, 2022. AP Photo/Rogelio V. Solis)&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/>;&lt;span>;FILE - The familiar sign at the Amazon Robotic Sorting Fulfillment Center in Madison County, Miss., Thursday, Aug. 11, 2022. AP Photo/Rogelio V. Solis)&lt;/span>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;Food company General Mills was among the companies closest to meeting the 2030 targets, at 65 percent.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Mary Jane Melendez is the company&#39;s chief sustainability officer. She said 85 percent of the company&#39;s water use is in agriculture. Extreme weather in the US has reportedly affected the company in recent years.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Melendez gave examples of weather-related problems. She said freezing and &lt;strong>;thawing&lt;/strong>; hurt the company&#39;s supply of sugar beets. She also said drought affected its oats supply.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Michael Kiparsky is director of the Wheeler Water Institute at the University of California, Berkeley. He said that corporations have an interest in protecting their operations from water shortages. That could push them to make bigger steps to protect freshwater resources.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kiparsky pointed out there is no way to enforce Ceres&#39; targets. But he asked, “Does money talk? When it talks, it talks pretty loud,&quot; he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;I&#39;m Dan Novak.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Dan Novak adapted this story for VOA Learning English based on reporting by The Associated Press. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;_______________________________________________&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>; &lt;/h2>; &lt;h2>;Words in This Story&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;drought &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— n. &lt;/em>;a period of much less rain than normal&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;sustainability &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— n. &lt;/em>;the ability to continue to use a resource without using it up&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;factor –&lt;/strong>;n. Something that produces a result&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;access &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— n. &lt;/em>;the ability to get or use something&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;sanitation &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;—&lt;/em>;&lt;em>; n. &lt;/em>;the equipment and structures needed to process waste and wastewater in a place&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;efficient &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— adj. &lt;/em>;using the right amount of a resource without using too much&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;watershed &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— n. &lt;/em>;the land area drained by a large river system&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;vast &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— adj. v&lt;/em>;ery large or wide&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;thaw &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— v. &lt;/em>;when ice or something that is frozen returns to a higher temperature and melts&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 03 Nov 2023 06:07:03 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[What Is Daylight Saving Time?]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/what-is-daylight-saving-time-/7337733.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;Thu, 02 Nov 2023 21:58:00 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/254d61cd-1052-4ed0-9207-7741fd073a83_cx0_cy4_cw0_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;FILE - Clocks are displayed at Electric Time Company on Nov. 1, 2022, in Medfield, Massachusetts. (AP Photo/Charles Krupa)&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;As November begins, many countries in North America and Europe are turning the clock back as daylight saving time ends.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Daylight saving time is the practice of moving clocks forward by one hour during summer months so daylight lasts longer into the evening.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In Europe, the practice is called European Summer Time. The clock usually moves forward in March and turns back at the end of October. Most European countries follow the practice. Georgia, Russia, Turkey, Iceland and a few others are among the exceptions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Across the Atlantic Ocean, Canada, Mexico, Cuba and the United States start daylight saving time in March also. The clock will be set back an hour on November 5 this year.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Countries closer to the equator usually do not follow daylight saving time because the period of daylight changes little. Those that do not change the times include countries in Central America, Asia and Africa.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;How did it start?&lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The idea of changing the clocks with the seasons started with &lt;a href=&quot;https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/3h42/hudson-george-vernon&quot;>;George Hudson&lt;/a>;, a New Zealand scientist who studied insects. In 1895, Hudson proposed a time change to extend summer daylight hours. The extra time would have helped him with collecting insects after work.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The idea did not appeal to anyone until the time of World War I when European countries sought to save energy. Germany was the first country to adopt daylight saving time, in 1916, and the US followed in 1918.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Some people believe that the US established daylight saving time to help farmers. But farmers generally do not like the practice. The publication &lt;a href=&quot;https://modernfarmer.com/2022/03/daylight-saving-time-farmers/&quot;>;Modern Farmer&lt;/a>; said American farmers were against the practice but that Congress approved it anyway.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Opponents of daylight saving time have pointed to studies that found an increase in traffic accidents, health issues, and lack of sleep in the days after clocks are moved forward every March.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;As for saving energy, the Congressional Research Service said studies have found little, if any, energy savings from the time change.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;Arguments to end the practice&lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Daylight saving time has been a fluid issue from the start. Some countries have adopted and rejected it several times. In South America, Uruguay ended the practice in 2015. Chile replaced it with “wintertime” from May to August in 2016.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Egypt announced in March it would return to daylight saving time after seven years to save energy. Japan briefly considered adopting the practice for the 2020 Olympics but rejected it due to a lack of popular support.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the US there have been several efforts to make daylight saving time permanent. Last year, a bill called the “Sunshine Protection Act” passed the Senate but got stuck in the House of Representatives. Lawmakers could not agree on whether to keep standard time or permanent daylight saving time.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The bill was proposed again this year.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;I&#39;m Caty Weaver.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Hai Do wrote this story for Learning English with additional reporting from Reuters.&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 03 Nov 2023 06:07:03 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Grammar and Optimism]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/grammar-and-optimism-/7334755.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;Thu, 02 Nov 2023 22:02:00 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/01000000-0a00-0242-285f-08dbda3b8e24_r1_s.png&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>; &lt;p>;How do we talk about events or actions that make us happy or hopeful about the present and future? In other words, how do we talk about &lt;strong>;optimism&lt;/strong>;?&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;In today&#39;s &lt;em>;Everyday Grammar&lt;/em>;, we will explore a point of connection between grammar and hopeful ideas about the future. You will learn how to understand the difference between closely related words – and how to use them in sentences.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Let&#39;s start with some important terms.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;History and relationships &lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Today&#39;s lesson begins with a noun: optimism. It is a feeling or belief that good things will happen in the future.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;The online Etymology Dictionary &lt;strong>;traces &lt;/strong>;the roots of the word “optimism” to 1759. The word first appeared in&lt;strong>; translations&lt;/strong>; from the French writer Voltaire.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;We also have a closely related noun that appeared in English at about the same time: optimist.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;An optimist is a person with a hopeful way of looking at things.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;The two nouns differ by only one letter. Optimism ends in an –m and suggests a general feeling or belief. Optimist ends with a –t and means a person with a hopeful world view.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;From optimist, we can add an –ic ending to get an adjective. Optimistic describes a person who is hopeful about the future or expects good things to happen.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;From optimistic, we can add an –ally ending to get an adverb: optimistically. This word describes or modifies verbs.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;So, we have a family of words. We have two nouns: optimism and optimist. From the noun optimist, we can add more letters to get the adjective, optimistic, and the adverb, optimistically.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;Usage &lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Now, how do we use these words in everyday discussions?&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;It is important to remember that some words are commonly used together. You might think of these as high-frequency structures, or word groups you see or hear a lot in speech and writing. What are some of these high-frequency structures?&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Let&#39;s start with optimism.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Google&#39;s Ngram Viewer tells us that the most commonly used word before “optimism” is the short word “of.”&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;For example, we might say the following:&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;At that time, people in the streets were happy; the economy was strong. A feeling of optimism was in the air.&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;What about the noun “optimist”?&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Once again, Google&#39;s Ngram Viewer tells us that another short word is commonly used before the noun “optimist.” In this case, the short word is “an.”&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;So, you are likely to hear or read something like this:&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;I am an optimist. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Or&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;She is an optimist.&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;What about the adjective “optimistic?” Once again, Google&#39;s Ngram Viewer tells us that the short word “an” is the most commonly used word before “optimistic.”&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;So, you are likely to hear or read something like the following:&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;He gave an optimistic answer. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Finally, we have the adverb “optimistically.” What is the most commonly used word before it? In this case, we have the verb “said.” You are likely to hear or read something like this:&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;The traffic doesn&#39;t look too bad, she said optimistically. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;Quiz &lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Now let&#39;s take some time to work with these ideas.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Fill in the blank with the correct word – either noun, adjective, or adverb.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;She spoke ____________ about the country&#39;s economic outlook. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;The correct word is the adverb optimistically. The sentence is “She spoke optimistically about the country&#39;s economic outlook.”&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;We know that the adverb is needed because it is modifying or describing the verb “spoke.” How did she speak? She spoke optimistically.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;Now let&#39;s consider another example. Fill in the blank.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p style=&quot;margin-left:40px&quot;>;&lt;em>;Tom is always so hopeful. He&#39;s an _________ at heart. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;The correct answer is the noun optimist. The full statement is “Tom is always so hopeful. He&#39;s an optimist at heart.”&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;We know that the answer is optimist because the words coming before optimist suggest a noun phrase. When we see the short word “an,” that tells us that a noun or noun phrase is coming.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;Closing thoughts &lt;/strong>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;In today&#39;s report, we explored a few closely related words. We also learned about commonly used structures.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;There are, of course, other ways to talk about hopeful views or ideas about the future. But that will have to be the subject of another lesson.&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;I&#39;m John Russell.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;John Russell wrote this lesson for VOA Learning English. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;_________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;h2>;Words in This Story&lt;/h2>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;optimism&lt;/strong>;&lt;em>; – n.&lt;/em>; a feeling or belief that good things will happen in the future&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;trace &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;–v.&lt;/em>; to follow the path of something&lt;/p>; &lt;/div>; &lt;div>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;translate&lt;/strong>; &lt;em>;– v. &lt;/em>;to change words from one language into another language&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 03 Nov 2023 06:07:03 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Study: Africa Unlikely to Expand Manufacturing]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/study-africa-unlikely-to-expand-manufacturing/7332998.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;Wed, 01 Nov 2023 21:55:48 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/09d40000-0a00-0242-44a7-08da90ec6240_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;FILE - A woman spins raw silk yarn in a factory owned by Rwandan textile firm Utexwra in Kigali January 19, 2009. A recent study says African countries are less likely to follow East Asia&#39;s development model of expanding manufacturing to reduce poverty.(REUTERS/Hereward Holland)&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;A recent study says African countries are less likely to follow East Asia&#39;s development model of expanding manufacturing to reduce &lt;strong>;poverty&lt;/strong>;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The study predicts a decreasing share of factory jobs for most countries by 2050.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Center for Global Development (CGD) released the study this week. It said there will be fewer factory workers around the world in 2050. And the paper predicts that, even in poor countries with a lot of low-cost labor, manufacturing job growth will slow down.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;China may be an&lt;strong>; exception &lt;/strong>;out of the 59 countries modeled in the study. The study said that China will continue to expand its share of manufacturing to 43.8 percent in 2050 from 30 percent in 2018 and 10.5 percent in 1975.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The study&#39;s writers said that China will continue its strong manufacturing performance, producing higher-valued products.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;This might create some space for developing countries in Africa, Southeast Asia, and South and Central America to start producing the products China will no longer produce. However, it will not be enough for other countries to follow the same development path taken by East Asia in expanding manufacturing.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Charles Kenny and Ranil Dissanayake of CGD said that many countries will move straight from agriculture to services. They say jobs will greatly expand in services because of new technologies – even in countries such as Bangladesh and Ethiopia.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“There&#39;s still a popular idea that low-income countries will progress naturally from being &lt;strong>;dominated&lt;/strong>; by agriculture to manufacturing-led growth, but &lt;strong>;mounting&lt;/strong>; evidence suggests that&#39;s not going to happen,” said Kenny. He said people think that farms are going to empty out across Africa and Asia in the coming years, but he said, people are likely to flood into offices and stores, not factories.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The study &lt;strong>;projects&lt;/strong>; worldwide growth through the year 2050. It aims to predict changes in the economies of 59 countries that make up about three quarters of the world&#39;s GDP and population.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;GDP, or gross domestic product, measures all the goods and services produced in a country in a year. GDP is considered a good measure of the size of a nation&#39;s economy.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The study projects that even for the lowest-income countries, the number of factory jobs will just keep up with population growth over the next 30 years. And it projects manufacturing will likely stay a small part of most of these countries&#39; economies.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Across all low-income countries, manufacturing jobs are projected to remain below eight percent of total employment. The study projects the share of manufacturing jobs in high-income countries will continue to fall, to 8.3 percent by 2050 from 11.4 percent currently.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Jobs in private service industries are expected to make up 37 percent of worldwide jobs by 2050, and 26 percent in low-income countries. That is up from about 12 percent currently.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;I&#39;m Gregory Stachel.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Reuters reported this story. Gregory Stachel adapted the story for VOA Learning English. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;________________________________________________&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>; &lt;/h2>; &lt;h2>;Words in This Story&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;poverty &lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;. the state of being poor&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;exception &lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;n&lt;/em>;. someone or something that is different from others&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;dominate &lt;/strong>;– &lt;em>;v&lt;/em>;. to be the most important part of (something)&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;mounting &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;– v.&lt;/em>; to increase in amount&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;project &lt;/strong>;–v. to estimate or predict something for a time in the future&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 02 Nov 2023 06:07:05 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Funding Cuts Threaten Refugee’s Children Education in Rwanda]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/funding-cuts-threaten-refugee-s-children-education-in-rwanda/7323250.html]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;Wed, 01 Nov 2023 21:57:00 GMT&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://images.weserv.nl?url=gdb.voanews.com/01000000-0aff-0242-4b8f-08dbd6299e2d_r1_s_w900.jpg&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot;>;&lt;div>;&lt;small style=&quot;color: #999;&quot;>;FILE — Hutu refugees women and children wait to be registered at Kigali airport Rwanda, after they arrived on the UN plane from Kisangai, Zaire Sunday, May 4, 1997. (AP Photo/Sayyid Azim, File)&lt;/small>;&lt;/div>; &lt;p>;Cuts to United Nations aid for refugees living in Rwanda are threatening education for children from more than 100,000 families. The families fled conflict in several East African countries. They are spread among five refugee camps in Rwanda.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Burundian refugee Epimaque Nzohoraho spoke about the situation to the&lt;em>; Associated Press&lt;/em>;. He said the leader of his son&#39;s school reported that his child should not return to class because the UN refugee agency had stopped paying for the education.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Nzohoraho said he does not know how much it costs to attend the school. But, he said, he had hoped education would save his son&#39;s future.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Last weekend, the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, UNHCR, announced budget cuts for food, education, shelter and health care. The agency acted as hopes disappear to meet the $90.5 million in aid donations.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;UNHCR spokesperson Lilly Carlisle said that only $33 million had arrived by October. “The agency cannot &lt;strong>;manage&lt;/strong>; to meet the needs of the refugees,” she said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Rwanda is home to a little more than 134,500 refugees. About 62 percent of them came from neighboring Congo. About 37 percent came from Burundi. Less than one percent are from other countries, says the country&#39;s emergency management ministry.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Among those affected are 553 refugee schoolchildren who were expecting to go to &lt;strong>;boarding&lt;/strong>; schools this year. The budget shortfall will not permit their attendance. The UNCHR is already supporting 750 students in boarding schools, Carlisle said. The school fees for boarding schools in Rwanda is $80 each school term.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Budget problems have also affected food&lt;strong>; &lt;/strong>;assistance, which has dropped from $5 to $3 per refugee monthly since last year.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Chantal Mukabirori is a Burundian refugee living in eastern Rwanda&#39;s Mahama camp. She says with reduced food aid, her four children are going hungry and refusing to go to school.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Do you expect me to send children to school when I know there is no food?” she asked.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Carlisle is urging refugees to “to look for employment to support their families,” but some say this is hard to do as a refugee.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Solange Uwamahoro fled violence in Burundi in 2015 after an attempted government overthrow. She says going back to the same country where her husband was killed may be her only choice.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I have no other &lt;strong>;option&lt;/strong>; now. I could die of hunger … it&#39;s very hard to get a job as a refugee,” Uwamahoro told the AP.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Phillipe Babinshuti is secretary of Rwanda&#39;s emergency management ministry. He says the refugees in Rwanda should not be forgotten even with the increasing number of global conflicts.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The aid reduction effect on education is likely to lower school enrollment. Data from UNHCR in 2022 showed that 1.1 million of 2.2 million refugee children in the East, Horn of Africa and Great Lakes area were out of school.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;I&#39;m Dan Novak.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;Dan Novak adapted this story for VOA Learning English based on reporting by the Associated Press. &lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;____________________________________________&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>; &lt;h2>; &lt;/h2>; &lt;h2>;Words in This Story&lt;/h2>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;manage &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— v. &lt;/em>;to have control of&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;boarding school &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— n. &lt;/em>;a school where students can live during the school term&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;option &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— n. &lt;/em>;the opportunity or ability to choose something or to choose between two or more things&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;strong>;enroll &lt;/strong>;&lt;em>;— v. &lt;/em>;to become a member or participant&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; &lt;/p>; &lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;获取更多RSS：&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.best&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.best&lt;/a>;&lt;br>;&lt;/div>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 02 Nov 2023 06:07:05 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>